ed States\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Deluxe\n| rowspan=\"2\" | CD\n| 50281802\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref name=\"TargetUS\" />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Japan\n| {{hlist|[[Hostess Entertainment|Hostess]]|[[Universal Music Group|UMG]]}}\n| BGJ-5252\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://store.universal-music.co.jp/product/bgj5252/|title=25 [Japan Bonus Track] by Adele|date=20 November 2015|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | South Korea\n|| 2 December 2015\n| rowspan=\"3\"|Standard\n| rowspan=\"2\"|{{hlist|CD|digital download}}\n|| Kang&Music\n| KACD1508\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>[http://hanteo.com/search/album_info.asp?mcode=029905125 Adele \u2013 25] at Hanteo</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | China\n|| 21 December 2015\n|| {{hlist|BeggarsChina-XL|Starsing}}\n| 9787883258315\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>[http://beggarschina.lofter.com/ Adele \u2013 25] at BeggarsChina-XL Recordings</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Various<!-- Spotify is not Worldwide. See [[Spotify#Geographic availability]]. Worldwide = the Total inhabited land mass of the planet. -->\n|| 24 June 2016\n| {{hlist|[[Media streaming|Streaming]]}}\n|| {{hlist|XL|Columbia}}\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web|last1=Ingham|first1=Tim|title=Adele's 25 is finally on Spotify... seven months after release|url=http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/adeles-25-finally-spotify-seven-months-release|website=Music Business Worldwide|accessdate=24 June 2016|date=24 June 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of best-selling albums]]\n* [[List of best-selling albums in Australia]]\n* [[List of best-selling albums in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[List of best-selling albums of the 2010s in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[List of best-selling albums of the 2000s (century) in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[List of best-selling albums in the United States]]\n* [[List of fastest-selling albums]]\n* [[List of Billboard 200 number-one albums of 2015|List of ''Billboard'' 200 number-one albums of 2015]]\n* [[List of Billboard 200 number-one albums of 2016|List of ''Billboard'' 200 number-one albums of 2016]]\n* [[List of number-one albums of 2015 (Australia)]]\n* [[List of number-one albums of 2016 (Australia)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://adele.com}}\n\n{{Adele}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for ''25''\n| titlestyle = background: lightblue\n| list1 =\n{{Brit British Album}}\n{{Grammy Award for Album of the Year}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album}}\n{{Juno Award for International Album of the Year}}\n}}\n{{IFPI Global Year-End}}\n{{Billboard Year-End number one albums}}\n{{UK Christmas No. 1 albums in the 2010s}}\n{{UK best-selling albums (by year) 2010\u20132029}}\n\n[[Category:2015 albums]]\n[[Category:Adele albums]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Ariel Rechtshaid]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Danger Mouse (musician)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Greg Kurstin]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Linda Perry]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Mark Ronson]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Max Martin]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Paul Epworth]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Ryan Tedder]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Samuel Dixon]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Shellback (record producer)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by The Smeezingtons]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Album of the Year]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album]]\n[[Category:Juno Award for International Album of the Year albums]]\n[[Category:Brit Award for British Album of the Year]]\n[[Category:Folk albums by English artists]]\n[[Category:XL Recordings albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = 25\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Adele]]\n| cover        = Adele - 25 (Official Album Cover).png\n| border       = \n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|df=yes|2015|11|20}}\n| recorded     = 2013\u201315\n| venue        = \n| studio       = {{collapsible list|title={{nobold|Various}}|hlist=true|[[Metropolis Group|Metropolis Studios]], London|MXM Studios, Stockholm|Eastcote Studios, London|The Church Studios, London|[[Dean Street Studios]], London|[[Associated Independent Recording|Air Studios]], London|[[British Grove Studios]], London|West Point Studios, London|Sam's Studio, London|Zelig Studios, London|Smecky Studios, Prague|Glenwood Recording Studios, Los Angeles|Greenleaf Studios, Los Angeles|Harmony Studios, Los Angeles|Vox Recording Studios, Los Angeles|Diamond Mine, New York}}\n| genre        = {{hlist|[[Soul music|Soul]]<ref name=Rosen />|[[Pop music|pop]]<ref name=Handy />|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=Rosen />}}\n| length       = {{Duration|m=48|s=25}}\n| label        = {{hlist|[[XL Recordings|XL]]|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]}}\n| producer     = {{hlist|[[Danger Mouse (musician)|Danger Mouse]]|[[Samuel Dixon]]|[[Paul Epworth]]|[[Greg Kurstin]]|[[Max Martin]]|[[Linda Perry]]|[[Ariel Rechtshaid]]|[[Mark Ronson]]|[[Shellback (record producer)|Shellback]]|[[The Smeezingtons]]|[[Ryan Tedder]]}}\n| prev_title   = [[Live at the Royal Albert Hall (Adele album)|Live at the Royal Albert Hall]]\n| prev_year    = 2011\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = 25\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Hello (Adele song)|Hello]]\n | single1date = 23 October 2015\n | single2     = [[When We Were Young (Adele song)|When We Were Young]]\n | single2date = 22 January 2016\n | single3     = [[Send My Love (To Your New Lover)]]\n | single3date = 16 May 2016\n | single4     = [[Water Under the Bridge (song)|Water Under the Bridge]]\n | single4date = 4 November 2016\n}}\n}}\n'''''25''''' is the third [[studio album]] by English singer-songwriter [[Adele]], released on 20 November 2015 by [[XL Recordings]] and [[Columbia Records]]. Issued nearly five years after her previous album, the internationally successful ''[[21 (Adele album)|21]]'' (2011), the album is titled as a reflection of her life and frame of mind at 25 years old and is termed a \"make-up record\". Its lyrical content features themes of Adele \"yearning for her old self, her nostalgia\", and \"melancholia about the passage of time\" according to an interview with the singer by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', as well as themes of motherhood and regret. In contrast to Adele's previous works, the production of ''25'' incorporated the use of electronic elements and creative rhythmic patterns, with elements of 1980s [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] and organs. Like when recording ''21'', Adele worked with producer and songwriter [[Paul Epworth]] and [[Ryan Tedder]], along with new collaborations with [[Max Martin]] and [[Shellback (record producer)|Shellback]], [[Greg Kurstin]], [[Danger Mouse (musician)|Danger Mouse]], [[the Smeezingtons]], [[Samuel Dixon]], and [[Tobias Jesso Jr]].\n\nUpon its release, ''25'' received generally positive reviews from critics, who commended Adele's vocal performance and the album's production. It was a massive commercial success, debuting at number one in 32 countries and [[List of fastest-selling albums|breaking first-week sales records]] in multiple countries, including the United Kingdom and United States. In the US, the album sold over 3.38 million copies in its first week of sales, marking the largest single-week sales for an album since [[Nielsen SoundScan]] began tracking point-of-sale music purchases in 1991. ''25'' eventually became the [[List of best-selling albums#Best-selling album by year worldwide|world's best-selling album of the year]] for 2015, with 17.4 million copies sold within the year,<ref name=\"IFPI\">{{cite web|title=Global Music Report|url=http://www.ifpi.org/downloads/GMR2016.pdf|publisher=[[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]]|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> and has gone on to sell over 22 million copies worldwide, making it one of the [[List of best-selling albums|best-selling albums of all time]], and the [[List of best-selling albums of the 21st century|fourth-best selling album of the 21st century]]. Following ''21'', it was [[RIAA certification|certified Diamond]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), denoting equivalent sales of 10 million copies in the US, making Adele the only artist of the 2010s to achieve this certification with two albums.\n\nGlobally, ''25'' was the biggest-selling music release in 2015 and 2016, with many journalists crediting it with impacting the music industry by encouraging a renewed interest in buying physical releases rather than downloading or streaming; much like ''21'', it was also credited for saving the dwindling sales of the UK and US music industry. ''25'' received the [[Brit Awards|BRIT Award]] for [[Brit Award for British Album of the Year|British Album of the Year]], while its lead single \"[[Hello (Adele song)|Hello]]\" won [[Brit Award for British Single of the Year|British Single of the Year]] at the [[2016 Brit Awards]]. It also won the [[2017 Grammy Awards]] for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]], and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]]; \"Hello\" also won Grammys for [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]], and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]]. To promote the album, Adele embarked on her third worldwide concert tour, [[Adele Live 2016]]. It started on 29 February 2016 and ended on 30 June 2017.\n\n==Background==\n\nFollowing the release of ''[[21 (Adele album)|21]]'' (2011), Adele was considering quitting music. However, in early 2012 she announced she was simply taking a hiatus from music in order to \"take time and live a little bit\".<ref name=\"MTV2012\">Kaufman, Gil (3 April 2012) [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1682315/adele-new-single.jhtml \"Adele To Release New Single This Year\"]. MTV. Retrieved 19 October 2012</ref> Her hiatus from music came to an end after the birth of her first child in October 2012, with Adele stating her son inspired her to start recording music again in order for him to \"know what I do\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://radio.com/2015/10/23/adele-admits-almost-quitting-music-after-21-in-interview-with-carson-daly/|title=Adele Admits Almost Quitting Music After '21'|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=26 October 2015|publisher=Radio.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160327085021/http://radio.com/2015/10/23/adele-admits-almost-quitting-music-after-21-in-interview-with-carson-daly/|archive-date=27 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474548/adele-gives-birth-to-baby-boy-reports|title=Adele Gives Birth to Baby Boy|newspaper=Billboard|date=21 October 2012}}</ref> Before the album's recording came under way, Adele made a conscious decision not to try and create another ''21'' and would not make another \"heartbreak record\".<ref name=\"id.vice.com\" />\n\nPrior to the album's release, ''25'' was listed as one of the most anticipated albums of 2015. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', ''[[Fuse (TV channel)|Fuse]]'', ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' and numerous others placed the album at number one on their most anticipated list, with the latter stating \"if Adele releases her third album in 2015, she could dominate the year.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/most-anticipated-albums-of-2015-adele-to-led-zeppelin-via-kanye-west-20150106-12ijeu.html|title=Most anticipated albums of 2015: Adele to Led Zeppelin, via Kanye West|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=6 January 2015|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> Prior to the album's official announcement, music journalists and fans speculated that the album would be titled ''25'' continuing the age theme from Adele's previous releases ''[[19 (Adele album)|19]]'' and ''[[21 (Adele album)|21]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/photos/6406578/30-most-anticipated-albums-of-2015|title=30 Most Anticipated Albums of 2015|work=Billboard|date=30 December 2014|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2015/01/30-most-anticipated-albums-of-2015|title=30 Most Anticipated Albums of 2015|publisher=Fuse|date=13 January 2015|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> On the eve of her 26th birthday in May 2014, Adele posted a message via her Twitter account which prompted media discussion about her next album. The message, \"Bye bye 25&nbsp;... See you again later in the year\", was interpreted by outlets including ''Billboard'' and [[Capital (radio network)|Capital FM]] as meaning that her next album would be titled ''25'' and released later in the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6077490/adele-new%20album-25-twitter-tease|title=Adele Teases '25' Album on Twitter?|work=Billboard|date=5 May 2014|accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.capitalfm.com/artists/adele/news/new-album-25-on-twitter/|title=Adele Teases New Album '25' On Twitter|publisher=Capital FM|date=5 May 2014|accessdate=5 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Writing and recording ==\n\n=== Early sessions and writer's block ===\n[[File:RyanTedderphotocall.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Sessions with [[Ryan Tedder]] were unfruitful, though he and Adele co-wrote \"Remedy\".]]\nOn 10 February 2013, Adele confirmed that she was in the very early stages of her third album and was having meetings while staying in Los Angeles for the [[85th Academy Awards]].<ref name=\"newalbumconfirmation\">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1538764/adele-talks-new-music-in-los-angeles|title=Adele Talks New Music in Los Angeles|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=19 October 2012|accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/adele/68983|title=Adele says she'll record a new album when she 'has something to sing about'|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=18 January 2014|date=2 March 2013}}</ref> Initially recording sessions for ''25'' were unsuccessful, in which Adele suffered from [[writer's block]]. Adele rescheduled the album's recording stating she did not feel \"ready\", but returned to the studio when her son was eighteen months old, which inspired her to write an album about motherhood.<ref name=\"billboard.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6738265/adele-return-25-hello-interviews|title=Adele on Her Return: 'I Was So Frightened That No One Cared'|work=Billboard|accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7612600/adele-25-new-album-scrapped-motherhood-baby|title=Adele Scrapped A \"Boring\" Album About Motherhood Before '25'|publisher=Idolator|accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref> In an interview on [[BBC One]], it was revealed that a whole album about being a mother was written and scrapped because she thought the material was \"too boring\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-34613748|title=Adele premieres 'intimate' new song|work=BBC News|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAdele stated that the album took a long time to write, saying she did not think the album was ever going to be finished.<ref name=\"hitsdailydouble.com\">{{cite web|url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/news&id=298186|title=Rumor Mill \u2013 ADELE RULES iTUNES IN 85 COUNTRIES (UPDATE)|work=HITS Daily Double|accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref> During the initial recording Adele ran out of ideas and lost the ability to write songs, but her team encouraged her to go back to the drawing board and keep writing.<ref name=\"hitsdailydouble.com\" /> After what seemed like a very arduous process to the singer, who feared she may have lost the inspiration for her writing, the material that eventually became ''25'' manifested. Adele attempted to write ''25'' numerous times, but struggled; after taking time off due to motherhood Adele returned to the studio but stated she was not ready to start writing. She then went on to take more time off, repeating this process \"a couple of times\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/article/adele-bbc-radio-2-25-interview|title=Adele Discusses New Album, Motherhood in BBC Radio Interview|work=People|first=Philip|last=Boucher|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{Listen\n| filename = Adele - Remedy Clip.ogg\n| title=\"Remedy\"\n| description=\"Remedy\" was conceived during a writing session with Ryan Tedder. Described as \"beautiful\" and \"heartfelt\",<ref name=\"mtv.com\" /> it was written about the singer's best friend, her grandparents, her boyfriend, and her son. Upon the song's conception, Adele was excited and believed she was finally creating music that she liked and felt confident about. The song was described as \"sassy\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Forrester|first=Katy|title=Adele's new album 25 reviewed track-by-track using her own facial expressions|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/adeles-new-album-25-reviewed-6860570}}</ref> and an \"earnest expression of devotion\".<ref>{{cite web|first=Rob|last=Garratt|title=Adele's 25 track-by-track|url=http://www.thenational.ae/arts-life/music-reviews/review-adeles-25-track-by-track}}</ref>\n|pos=right\n}}\nIn 2013, Adele began recording once again, contacting friend and producer [[Kid Harpoon]]. Adele and Harpoon went to his recording studio, however the session was unproductive with Adele saying: \"I don't know why I wasn't ready, I just couldn't access myself.\"<ref name=\"id.vice.com\">{{cite web|url=http://i-d.vice.com/en_gb/article/adele-exclusive-full-cover-story-i-d|title=adele interview: world exclusive first interview in three years|work=ID|date=29 October 2015|accessdate=6 November 2015|first=Hattie|last=Collins}}</ref>\nA few months passed and Adele travelled to New York to begin working with long time collaborator [[Ryan Tedder]], but the sessions with Tedder were also unfruitful.<ref name=\"id.vice.com\" /> However Adele did use one of the songs from the sessions entitled \"Remedy\", which was written about her best friend, her grandparents, her boyfriend, and her son. Adele was excited by the song and believed she was finally creating music that she liked and felt confident about. After recording the song along with others she flew producer [[Rick Rubin]] to the studio who was displeased with the songs that she had written, and encouraged Adele to go back to the \"drawing board\".<ref name=\"id.vice.com\" />\nRubin described the songs as having no depth and stated to Adele;\n\n{{quote|Adele was anxious to be finished with the new album and move forward with life, I stressed the most important thing was to be true to her voice, even if that took longer and was more work&nbsp;... In the new material I heard, it was clear she wasn't the primary writer \u2013 many of the songs sounded like they might be on a different pop artist's album. It's not just her voice singing any song that makes it special.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/adele-inside-her-private-life-and-triumphant-return-20151103|title=Adele: Inside Her Private Life and Triumphant Return|date=3 November 2015|accessdate=6 November 2015|journal=Rolling Stone|first=Brian|last=Hiatt}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Breakthrough sessions ===\nAdele continued to suffer with writer's block, until she met with producer [[Greg Kurstin]]. During the meeting with Kurstin, Adele had a breakthrough: \"It all poured right out of me.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/146974/adele-speaks-out-on-siriusxm-beats-radio-1-hello-e|title=Adele Speaks Out on SiriusXM, Beats Radio 1, 'Hello' Explodes Worldwide|work=All Access}}</ref> \"Hello\" was written by Adele and Kurstin and produced by the latter, who also played bass, guitar, piano and keyboards, with Adele being credited as a drummer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6738449/radio-on-adele-hello-she-can-make-you-feel-what-she-feels|title=Radio on Adele's 'Hello': 'She Can Make You Feel What She Feels'|work=Billboard}}</ref> The song was written in [[Chiswick]], London, something not normally done by Adele, who said she likes to write her music at home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p035zwgc|title=Adele: \"My son doesn't like my music, I just sing Twinkle Twinkle\"|publisher=BBC Radio 2|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref> The writing process for the song was slow, taking six months to complete. Initially Adele and Kurstin started writing the first verse; finishing half of the song, six months later Adele contacted Kurstin to finish the song with her, with Kurstin stating he was not sure \"if Adele was ever going to come back and finish it.\"<ref name=\"RTm\" />\nThe main inspiration behind the record came from her motherhood, as well as singer-songwriter [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s 1998 studio album, ''[[Ray of Light]]'', and its song \"[[Frozen (Madonna song)|Frozen]]\".<ref name=\"RTm\" /> Although Adele clarified that she \"wasn't exposed to Madonna's catalog earlier\" in life, she loved Madonna's electronic musical foray after hearing it. \"I believe everything she says on it. Some of the songs on it are an ode to her first kid, and I needed that to challenge me.\" Along with ''Ray of Light'', Adele also listened to musician [[Moby]]'s fifth studio album, ''[[Play (Moby album)|Play]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6770252/adele-25-album-release-party-nyc-joes-pub|title=10 Revelations From Adele's '25' Album Release Party|last=Lynch|first=Joe|date=20 November 2015|accessdate=21 November 2015|work=Billboard}}</ref>\n<blockquote>\nYou know what I found so amazing about [''Ray of Light'']?&nbsp;... That's the record Madonna wrote after having her first child, and for me, it's her best. I was so all over the place after having a child, just because my chemicals were just hitting the fucking roof and shit like that&nbsp;... I was just drifting away, and I couldn't find that many examples for myself where I was like, 'Fuck, they truly came back to themselves,' until someone was like, 'Well, obviously, ''Ray of Light''.'<ref name=\"RTm\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/adele-inside-her-private-life-and-triumphant-return-20151103?page=2|title=Adele: Inside Her Private Life and Triumphant Return|author=Brian Hiatt|work=[[RollingStone]]|date=3 November 2015|accessdate=4 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921164401/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/adele-inside-her-private-life-and-triumphant-return-20151103?page=2|archive-date=21 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n[[File:Electric Lady Studios 2013.jpg|right|thumb|The album was mixed at [[Electric Lady Studios]].]]\nDuring the album's recording Adele travelled to Los Angeles in order to give the recording sessions \"one last push\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/feature/a675199/adeles-new-single-first-listen-review-hello-is-a-mighty-comeback.html|title=Adele's new single first listen review: 'Hello' is a mighty comeback|work=Digital Spy|first=Lewis|last=Corner|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref> Adele spent two months in Los Angeles, and was determined to move forward with the album.<ref name=\"RTm\" /> During the sessions in Los Angeles she also wrote \"[[When We Were Young (Adele song)|When We Were Young]]\" alongside [[Tobias Jesso Jr.]], the track was written at a rented house where Adele used [[Philip Glass]]' piano.<ref name=\"billboard.com\" /> Adele also worked with singer-songwriter [[Bruno Mars]], initially the pair had attempted to create an uptempo song, however they created a \"dramatic ballad\" entitled \"[[All I Ask (Adele song)|All I Ask]]\".<ref name=\"RTm\" />\n\nAfter unfruitful sessions with Tedder, the pair went to lunch where Adele heard [[Taylor Swift]]'s single \"[[I Knew You Were Trouble]]\". Tedder informed Adele that the song was produced by [[Max Martin]], and sent her clips of his work.<ref name=\"id.vice.com\" /> Shortly after this, Adele began work on the track \"[[Send My Love (To Your New Lover)]]\", reworking a skeleton of a song she had written when she was thirteen years old after being inspired by the release of ''[[Frank (Amy Winehouse album)|Frank]]'' by [[Amy Winehouse]].<ref name=\"id.vice.com\" /> Kurstin also co-wrote and produced the song \"[[Million Years Ago (song)|Million Years Ago]]\". The song was not set to be included on the record, but was added three days prior to the album's mixing at [[Electric Lady Studios]] in New York.<ref name=\"id.vice.com\" />\n\n=== Scrapped tracks ===\nAdele co-wrote a song called \"[[Alive (Sia song)|Alive]]\" with Jesso and [[Sia Furler|Sia]]. Initially written for ''25'' along with \"[[Bird Set Free]]\" and another track, Adele decided not to include any of the songs on the album. Following Adele's decision, Sia asked her permission to send the track to [[Rihanna]], which Adele agreed to as long as her vocals were taken off the record, stating: \"I don't want my vocal floating around out there on a demo.\" Sia eventually recorded it herself for her seventh studio album ''[[This Is Acting]]''.<ref name=\"Stuff\">{{cite news|title=Sia: The songs from my new album were rejected by everyone else|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/72417244/sia-the-songs-from-my-new-album-were-rejected-by-everyone-else|work=Stuff.co.nz|accessdate=25 September 2015}}</ref>\n\"Bird Set Free\" was recorded by Adele, but she decided not to include it due to it being too similar to Sia's work; it too was subsequently included on ''This Is Acting''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7613619/sia-bird-set-free-listen-rejected-by-adele|title=Sia's 'Bird Set Free': Listen To Yet Another Song Rejected By Adele|publisher=Idolator|accessdate=6 November 2015|date=3 November 2015|first=Robbie|last=Daw}}</ref>\n\nBefore beginning work on the album, Adele met with [[Phil Collins]] to discuss a collaboration. \"I had this song in mind,\" she told ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', \"and I can't remember if I gave him a copy of the song or if I gave him a chorus or something, and then I just chickened out of everything.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Brian|last=Hiatt|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/17-things-you-learn-hanging-out-with-adele-20151130|title=17 Things You Learn Hanging Out With Adele|work=Rolling Stone|date=30 November 2015|accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> \"She's a slippery little fish\u2026\" Collins remarked subsequently. \"She got hold of me and asked if I would write with her. She gave me a piece of music to finish and at first I didn't know if I'd failed the audition as I didn't hear from her. Then she said, 'No, no: I'm moving house and the baby's taking up a lot of my time. I'm not actually doing anything at the moment.' And now I've heard there's a ''29'' [sic] coming out. I'm not on it, I know that.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Terri|last=White|title=Cash for questions|magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|date=December 2014|page=32}}</ref>\n\n== Musical style and themes ==\n{{Quote box\n|quote =\"My last record was a break-up record, and if I had to label this one, I would call it a make-up record. Making up for lost time. Making up for everything I ever did and never did. ''25'' is about getting to know who I've become without realising. And I'm sorry it took so long but, you know, life happened.\"|source = \u2014 Adele, on the album's lyrical content<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-34594035|title=Adele confirms new album is called 25|work=BBC News|date=21 October 2015|accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n |align=left\n |width = 22em\n}}\nConsisting of eleven tracks, Adele aimed to depart from the \"young-fogey\" sound of her second album ''21'' and added synths and drum pads in order to modernize ''25''{{'}}s musical style.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hiatt|first=Brian|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/adele-inside-her-private-life-and-triumphant-return-20151103|title=Adele: Inside Her Private Life and Triumphant Return|work=Rolling Stone|date=3 November 2015|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> The album's production incorporated the use of electronic elements and creative rhythmic patterns, unlike its predecessor, with elements of 1980s R&B and organs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/adele-25/|title=Adele: 25|work=PopMatters|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-adele-25-review-20151119-story.html|title=Adele returns to explain the big emotions of your life on '25'|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> Described as a collection of \"panoramic ballads and prettily executed detours\", Leah Greenblatt of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' noted the album's \"stately production\" characterizing it as being built over minor-key melancholy, stylistic flourishes and simplicity.<ref name=\"EW\"/> Leonie Cooper of the ''[[NME]]'' summed the album's production up as changing from \"moody balladeering to smoky jazz bar grooves\" whilst a reviewer from ''[[Us Weekly]]'' stated the album was built upon piano ballads, R&B grooves, minimalistic arrangements, gospel, blues and acoustic guitars.<ref name=\"nme\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Ian Drew|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/adeles-25-is-a-four-star-triumph-album-review-w157988|title=Adele's 25 Is a Four-Star \"Triumph\": Album Review|work=Us Weekly|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nAdele's vocals on ''25'' were described as being capable of conveying emotion.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lauren Murphy|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/adele-25-album-review-more-than-just-a-voice-more-than-just-a-break-up-album-1.2437348|title=Adele 25 album review \u2013 more than just a voice, more than just a break-up album|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref>\nHer vocals were noted by Samantha O'Connor of ''The 405'' as ranging from \"thunderous roars and rib-cracking falsettos over large dramatic piano swells to fuzzy, warm lower-register rumblings\", and were characterised as having a raw delivery, with minimal engineering, leaving \"her vocal idiosyncrasies to crackle, croak and coo, bringing more depth\" to the album.<ref name=\"thefourohfive1\">{{cite web|last=O'Connor|first=Samantha|url=http://www.thefourohfive.com/music/review/adele-25-144|title=Adele \u2013 25 \u2013 Review|publisher=Thefourohfive.com|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref>\nBruce Handy of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' stated that Adele's throat surgery had not impacted her voice, continuing to say her voice still contained character and power: \"brassy yet husky, smoky yet clarion, she still sounds like the result of a genetic experiment fusing [[Amy Winehouse]]'s vocal chords with [[C\u00e9line Dion]]'s lungs, or even [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]]'.\"<ref name=\"Handy\">{{cite web|last=Handy|first=Bruce|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2015/11/review-adele-25-album|title=Review: Adele's 25 Is the Confessional Blockbuster You Wanted It to Be|work=Vanity Fair|date=2 January 2014|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nDescribed by Adele as a \"make-up album\", she attempted to move away from the theme of break-ups that dominated ''21''{{'}}s lyrical content. Adele stated that ''25''{{'}}s lyrics focuses on themes of her \"trying to clear out the past,\" and moving on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/adele/89314|title=Adele says new album '25' is about 'trying to clear out the past'|work=NME|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref>\nShe continued to say that the album's lyrics are a reflection of the frame of mind she was in during that age, describing the time as a \"turning point\" where she was in the centre of adolescence and adulthood and the start of a time where she would \"go into becoming who I'm going to be forever without a removal van full of my old junk.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6737433/adele-new-album-25-release-letter|title=Adele Finally Shares Update on New Album '25': 'I'm Sorry It Took So Long'|work=Billboard|date=21 October 2015|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref>\nLyrically, the album touches upon various themes including the singers fear of getting older, her childhood, regrets, longing for her family, nostalgia and her role as a mother.<ref name=\"thefourohfive1\" />\nMark Savage of the [[BBC]], noted the album's themes were a departure from the anger and heartbroken themes that dominated ''21'', stating that the lyrics were \"reflective\" allowing the singer \"to re-examine her past relationships\". Savage continued to state that songs such as \"[[When We Were Young (Adele song)|When We Were Young]]\" introduce the album's key theme of Adele's \"uneasy acceptance of adulthood.\"<ref name=\"bbco\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34833655|title=Adele \u2013 25: A first listen \u2013 BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> The album is focused at a broad [[pop music|popular music]] appeal, where her former releases, were made with a concoction of \"gospel, R&B, jazz, [and] folk\" styles, elements, and audiences in mind.<ref name=\"Star Telegram Review\">{{cite journal|first=Preston|last=Jones|title=Adele gives us a Million reasons to love 25|url=http://www.star-telegram.com/entertainment/arts-culture/article45348795.html|journal=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]|accessdate=24 November 2015|date=18 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{Listen\n | filename = Adele - When We Were Young Clip.ogg\n | title = 'When We Were Young'\n | description = On \"When We Were Young\", the singer elevates \"maudlin sentiment into high art\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/17840-adele-when-we-were-young/|title=Adele: \"When We Were Young\"|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=23 November 2015|accessdate=11 December 2015|author=Gordon, Jeremy}}</ref> With a moderately slow [[tempo]] of 72 beats per minute, the Ariel Rechtshaid-produced song introduces the album's key theme of Adele's \"uneasy acceptance of adulthood\".<ref name=bbco />\n|pos=right }}\n\n=== Songs ===\n''25'' opens with \"[[Hello (Adele song)|Hello]]\", a piano [[ballad]] that borrows heavily from [[soul music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stereogum.com/1839280/adele-hello-video/mp3s/|title=Adele \u2013 \"Hello\" Video|work=Stereogum|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/10/adele-hello-single-cant-be-bothered-with-modern-technology.html|title=Adele's 'Hello' Rebuffs Modern Technology|work=Vulture|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref> During the chorus Adele is heard singing the lines over layers of backing vocals, piano and drums which were described by the ''Telegraph'' as leaning \"towards a very luscious wall of sound\".<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/artists/Adele-Hello-review/|title=Adele, 'Hello', review: 'delivers raw, honest feeling'|website=The Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref> The track also contains drums which Adele was credited for providing.<ref name=\"Billboard \u2013 Lars\">{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6738252/adele-comeback-song-hello-25|title=Adele's Comeback Song 'Hello' Has Arrived|last=Brandle|first=Lars|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> Lyrically, the track focuses on themes of nostalgia and regret and plays out like a conversation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/feature/a675199/adeles-new-single-first-listen-review-hello-is-a-mighty-comeback/|title=Adele's new single first listen review: 'Hello' is a mighty comeback|author=Lewis Corner|date=23 October 2015|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> The follow up, \"[[Send My Love (To Your New Lover)]]\", has been compared to the work of singer Taylor Swift<ref name=\"gleason1\">{{cite journal|last=Gleason|first=Holly|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/11/adele-25-review.html|title=Adele: ''25'' Review|journal=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|accessdate=23 November 2015|date=20 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/11/album-review-adele-25/|title=Adele \u2013 25|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref> due to its \"upbeat, poppy\" sound.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2015/11/20/adele-25-album-review/|title=Adele's '25' Album Review: Simple, Soulful, & Truly Sensational|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref> Adele describes it as a \"happy you're gone\" song, which was inspired by an ex-boyfriend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khvhradio.com/articles/entertainment-news-104658/adele-returns-to-joes-pub-for-14144798|title=Adele Returns To Joe's Pub For Intimate iHeartRadio Album Premiere|accessdate=23 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121194848/http://www.khvhradio.com/articles/entertainment-news-104658/adele-returns-to-joes-pub-for-14144798|archive-date=21 November 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe drum-filled [[Folk music|folk]] song \"I Miss You\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kentucky.com/entertainment/article45628818.html|title=Review: Adele's 25 lives up to all of its expectations|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref> has been described as \"explicitly seductive\" due to the lyrics: \"Bring the floor up to my knees/Let me fall into your gravity/And kiss me back to life to see/Your body standing over me.\"<ref name=\"EW\" /> \"[[When We Were Young (Adele song)|When We Were Young]]\", another piano-led ballad,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/adele-25-album-review-beautifully-crafted-record-that-misses-wow-factor-masterpiece-21-1529699|title=Beautifully crafted record that misses the \"wow\" factor masterpiece of 21|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref> is \"a reflective serenade about treasuring the moments you will look back on in years to come\",<ref name=\"digitalspy1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/album-reviews/review/a774491/adele-new-album-25-track-by-track-review/|title=It's here! Adele's new album 25 \u2013 Our track-by-track review|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref> while the ballad \"Remedy\", was written about Adele's best friend, her grandparents, her boyfriend, and her son.<ref name=\"id.vice.com\" />\n\"[[Water Under the Bridge (song)|Water Under the Bridge]]\" is a mid-tempo pop song,<ref name=\"digitalspy1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7615616/adele-25-review|title=Adele's 25: Album Review|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref> featuring an electro-drum beat and a [[Tropical music|tropical]], [[trip hop]] riff,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/photos/103869/adele-new-album-25-track-by-track-review-songs-lyrics|title=First listen: Our track by track review of Adele's 25|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref> with Adele proclaiming to her lover \"If you're gonna let me down, let me down gently/Don't pretend that you don't want me/Our love ain't water under the bridge\". The gospel-tinged \"[[River Lea (song)|River Lea]]\" talks about the singer growing up in [[Tottenham, London, England]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/11/20/adele-25-review-track-by-track-rated_n_8589942.html|title=Adele '25' Review: Track-By-Track Review Of 'Hello' Singer's New Album \u2013 The Follow Up to the 30-Million Selling '21'|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref>\nAdele sings about [[River Lea|The Lea]], a river in London. During the song Adele speaks of how the river's polluted waters have seeped into her blood causing her relationship failures.<ref name=\"mtv.com\">{{cite web|publisher=MTV|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2545399/adele-25-track-by-track-breakdown/|title=A Track-By-Track Breakdown of Adele's 25|date=20 November 2015|accessdate=24 December 2015}}</ref>\n\"Love in the Dark\" is a [[Torch song|torch]] ballad.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone review\" />\n\n\"[[Million Years Ago (song)|Million Years Ago]]\", an [[Acoustic music|acoustic]] tune accompanied only by guitar, finds the singer pining \"for the normality of her not-so-distant childhood. Entwined with Middle Eastern twists of background hums that suggest [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s '[[Frozen (Madonna song)|Frozen]]'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/11/23/457081463/review-adele-25|title=Review: Adele, '25'|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref>\nThe song's lyrics touch upon themes of fame, and how it \"frightens\", the song's lyrics talk about how fame has personally affected her and everyone around her, singing about how she misses the air, her mother, and her friends, but her \"life is flashing by and all I can do is watch and cry.\"<ref name=\"mtv.com\" />\nIn the final piano ballad \"All I Ask\",<ref name=\"Handy\" /> \"Adele addresses a lover on what she knows will be their final night, processing the end of an affair in what feels like slow motion.\"<ref name=\"Rolling Stone review\" /> ''25'' closes with \"Sweetest Devotion\", an \"uplifting\" number written as a tribute to her son.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/11/19/album-of-the-week-review-adele-25/75672282/|title=Adele rolls in deeper on her new album, 25|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Release and promotion ==\n{{Main|Adele at the BBC|Adele Live in New York City}}\nA release date for ''25'' was first suggested in early August 2014, when [[Paul Moss]] suggested that an album would be released in 2014 or 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Frank|first=Alex|url=http://www.vogue.com/1438555/rihanna-adele-frank-ocean-album-release-dates/|title=Waiting for New Albums From Rihanna, Adele, Frank Ocean, and Robyn|work=Vogue|date=11 September 2014|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref> However, accounts filed by Adele's label [[XL Recordings]] in October 2014 ruled out the possibility of a 2014 release. In August 2015, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' reported that Adele's label had intentions of releasing her third studio album sometime in November 2015.<ref>{{cite news|first=Amelia|last=Buttterly|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/29574448|title=No new Adele album in 2014, according to XL's accounts|work=[[Newsbeat]]|publisher=BBC|date=10 October 2014|accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2015/09/25/is-adeles-new-album-finally-coming-in-november/|title=Is Adele's New Album Finally Coming in November?|work=Forbes|first=Hugh|last=McIntyre|date=25 September 2015|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> In October 2015, the album was rumoured to be released on 20 November 2015, after which numerous journalists speculated that other musicians had brought forward their albums in order to avoid chart competition with her, with artists such as [[One Direction]], [[Justin Bieber]], [[Fleur East]], and [[5 Seconds of Summer]] releasing their albums before Adele's, so that their sales and chart placements would not be affected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/34570462/adeles-new-track-other-artists-pushed-material-back-to-avoid-clash|title=Adele's new track: Other artists pushed material back to avoid clash|publisher=BBC|date=19 October 2015|accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latinospost.com/articles/75325/20151013/adeles-new-album-25-to-be-epic-release-other-artists-advised-to-drop-their-records-at-a-later-date.htm|title=Adele's New Album '25' to be Epic Release, Other Artists Advised to Drop Their Records at a Later Date|work=Latinos Post|date=13 October 2015|accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref> The fourth quarter was also set to have releases from [[Rihanna]], [[Kanye West]], and [[Coldplay]], and all except Coldplay backed out from coinciding with the release of Adele's album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/news&id=298171|title=HITS Daily Double : Rumor Mill - FOUR WILD CARDS}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 October, a 30-second clip of \"[[Hello (Adele song)|Hello]]\" was shown on UK television during a commercial break on ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]''. It teased a new song from Adele after three years, with viewers hearing her singing the first verse of \"Hello\" with its lyrics appearing on a black screen.<ref name=\"Teaser\">{{cite news|title=Adele 'teases new material in TV advert'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34567653|publisher=BBC|date=18 October 2015}}</ref> Three days later, Adele released a letter to her fans through social media addressing the album, in which she confirmed that the album would be titled ''25''.<ref name=\"billboard1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6737433/adele-new-album-25-release-letter|title=Adele Finally Shares Update on New Album '25': 'I'm Sorry It Took So Long'|work=Billboard|date=24 February 2013|accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref> Adele stated that the title is a reflection on her age and the frame of mind she was in during that age, describing the time as a \"turning point\" where she was in the centre of adolescence and adulthood and the start of a time where she would \"go into becoming who I'm going to be forever without a removal van full of my old junk.\" She added: \"My last record was a break-up record and if I had to label this one I would call it a make-up record. I'm making up with myself. I'm making up for lost time.\"<ref name=\"billboard1\" /> Adele confirmed the next day ''25'' would be released on 20 November 2015, and revealed its cover simultaneously on her social media.<ref name=\"USiTunes\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/25/id1051394208|title=iTunes Music \u2013 25 by Adele|publisher=iTunes Store (US). Apple Inc.|date=20 November 2015|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"25 \u2013 Time\">{{cite news|title=Adele Just Shared the Release Date for New Album 25|url=http://time.com/4083224/adele-25-new-album-release-date/|last=Feeney|first=Nolan|date=22 October 2015|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 October, [[BBC One]] announced plans for a one-hour television special presented by [[Graham Norton]] in which he would talk to Adele about her new album. ''[[Adele at the BBC]]'' was recorded before a live audience on 2 November and transmitted on [[BBC One]] on 20 November, coinciding with the album's release.<ref name=Norton /> A short extract of the programme was previewed during an edition of BBC One's ''[[The One Show]]'' aired on 5 November; it shows Adele performing \"Hello\" and chatting to Norton.<ref>{{cite news|first=Nick|last=Barnes|url=http://www.unrealitytv.co.uk/showbiz/look-adele-at-the-bbc-preview-hear-her-sing-hello-live-for-the-first-time/|title=Adele performs Hello in 'Adele at the BBC' preview|publisher=UnrealityTV|date=5 November 2015|accessdate=5 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106212714/http://www.unrealitytv.co.uk/showbiz/look-adele-at-the-bbc-preview-hear-her-sing-hello-live-for-the-first-time/ |archive-date=6 November 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref> On 27 October it was also announced that the singer would make an appearance on the US entertainment series ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' on 21 November.<ref name=Norton>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34638507|title=Adele to film BBC One special with Graham Norton|work=BBC News|date=27 October 2015|accessdate=27 October 2015}}</ref> On 30 October, Adele confirmed through her Facebook page that she would be performing a one-night-only concert titled ''[[Adele Live in New York City]]'' at the [[Radio City Music Hall]] on 17 November. Subsequently, [[NBC]] confirmed they will air the concert special on 14 December.<ref>{{cite news|last=Goodman|first=Jessica|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/10/30/adele-live-new-york-city-radio-music-hall|title=Adele Live in New York CIty: Adele will perform at Radio City Music Hall for NBC special|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=30 October 2015|accessdate=30 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/10/30/adele-live-in-new-york-city-concert-special-nbc/74860420/|title=NBC plans 'Adele Live in New York City' concert special|newspaper=USA Today|date=30 October 2015|accessdate=30 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 November 2015, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that the album will not be released on streaming services, such as [[Spotify]] and [[Apple Music]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/20/business/media/adele-music-album-25.html|title=Adele Is Said to Reject Streaming for '25'|first=Ben|last=Sisario|work=The New York Times|date=19 November 2015|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> It was later announced that ''25'' would be made available through streaming services from 24 June 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-36618429|title=Adele's 25 to be available on streaming sites|work=BBC News|date=24 June 2016|accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> Also in November, Adele appeared on the [[NRJ Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6754075/watch-adele-deliver-powerful-hello-performance-at-frances-nrj-awards|title=Watch Adele Give Powerful 'Hello' Performance at France's NRJ Awards}}</ref> [[NPR]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/11/24/457252109/you-cant-prepare-yourself-a-conversation-with-adele|title='You Can't Prepare Yourself': A Conversation With Adele}}</ref> and ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc.com/the-tonight-show/guest/adele/206691|title=Adele Guests on The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon \u2013 NBC.com|last=NBC.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January, she sang some of her greatest hits so far during her carpool karaoke video on ''[[The Late Late Show with James Corden]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6843094/adele-james-corden-carpool-karaoke-late-late-show|title=Adele Raps, Sings Spice Girls with James Corden in 'Carpool Karaoke': Watch}}</ref> The following month, Adele performed at the [[2016 Grammy Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/grammys/6875269/adele-all-i-ask-performance-grammys-2016|title=Adele Performs Stirring Rendition of 'All I Ask' at 2016 Grammys}}</ref> the [[2016 Brit Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/6889491/adele-cries-curses-brit-awards-2016|title=Adele Cries, Curses After Accepting Global Success Award at 2016 Brit Awards}}</ref> and ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ellentv.com/tags/Adele/|title=Adele}}</ref> Adele also conducted interviews with and appeared on the covers of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/4155795/adele-time-cover-story-interview-motherhood-25/|title=Adele on Motherhood, Social Media and Breaking Records|first=Sam|last=Lansky|work=Time|date=21 December 2015|accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref> ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2016/10/adele-cover-story|title=Cover Story: Adele, Queen of Hearts|first=Lisa|last=Robinson|work=Vanity Fair|date=31 October 2016|accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref> ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/13393643/adele-march-2016-cover/|title=Adele Had Us Long Before \"Hello\"|first=Hamish|last=Bowles|work=Vogue|date=12 February 2016|accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref> ''[[i-D]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_gb/article/adele-exclusive-full-cover-story-i-d|title=adele interview: world exclusive first interview in three years|first=Hattie|last=Collins|publisher=i-D|date=26 November 2016|accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Observer]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/nov/15/adele-im-not-a-recluse-observer-interview|title=Adele: 'I'm not a recluse \u2013 but I'm not going to be endorsing any cars, toys or nail varnishes'|first=Vanessa|last=Thorpe|work=The Guardian|date=15 November 2015|accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/nov/15/adele-25-new-album-interview|title=Adele: 'I can finally reach out a hand to my ex. Let him know I'm over it'|work=The Guardian|date=15 November 2015|accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref> and ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/adele-inside-her-private-life-and-triumphant-return-20151103|title=Adele: Inside Her Private Life and Triumphant Return|first=Brian|last=Hiatt|work=Rolling Stone|date=3 November 2015|accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref> Adele performed \"Hello\" again at the [[2017 Grammy Awards]].\n\n=== Singles ===\nOn 23 October 2015, \"[[Hello (Adele song)|Hello]]\" was released as the album's [[lead single]] and was made available for purchase and streaming, with its music video released on the same day.<ref name=\"25 \u2013 Billboard\">{{cite news|title=Adele Reveals Release Date, Tracklist for '25' Album|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6737541/adele-25-album-release|last=Lynch|first=Joe|date=22 October 2015|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref> It compiled over 100 million views on [[YouTube]] within 5 days. It is the second-fastest video to hit 100 million YouTube views ever and the fastest to reach 100 million on [[Vevo]] previously held by \"[[Wrecking Ball (Miley Cyrus song)|Wrecking Ball]]\" by [[Miley Cyrus]] back in 2013.<ref name=\"26 \u2013 Billboard\">{{cite news|title=Adele's 'Hello' Is Second-Fastest Video to Hit 100 Million YouTube Views Ever|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6745988/adele-hello-fastest-youtube-100-million|last=Lynch|first=Joe|date=29 October 2015|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=30 October 2015}}</ref> 87 days after its release \"Hello\" had received a billion YouTube views, beating [[Psy]]'s \"[[Gangnam Style]]\", which had accumulated the same number of views over 158 days.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/35379481/adeles-hello-video-reaches-a-billion-views-on-youtube|title=Adele's Hello video reaches a billion views on YouTube|work=BBC Radio 1 Newsbeat|publisher=BBC|date=22 January 2016|accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> The song reached number one in the UK Singles Chart on 30 October, with a combined first week sales of 330,000 copies. The figure was the largest opening week sales for a single since [[James Arthur (singer)|James Arthur]]'s \"[[Impossible (James Arthur song)|Impossible]]\", which achieved a volume of 490,000 sales in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34680904|title=Adele's Hello tops UK singles chart|work=BBC News|date=30 October 2015|accessdate=30 October 2015}}</ref> The song sold 1,112,000 digital downloads and 61.2 million streams in its first week, resulting in \"Hello\" debuting at number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] (becoming Adele's fourth number-one single in the United States) on the issue dated 14 November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6746355/adele-hello-no-1-hot-100-debut-one-million-downloads-week|title=Adele Says 'Hello' to No. 1 Hot 100 Debut; First Song to Sell 1 Million Downloads in a Week|work=Billboard}}</ref> By the end of 2015, it had sold 12.3 million units globally and was the year's 7th best-selling single.<ref name=\"IFPI\" />\n\nOn 14 December 2015, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' reported that \"[[When We Were Young (Adele song)|When We Were Young]]\" is scheduled as the second single from ''25''. The song had already charted at number 29 on the [[UK Single Chart]] and number 22 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, and sold 150,000 digital copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Adele's 'When We Were Young' Confirmed As Second Single From '25'|first=Gary|last=Trust|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6806119/adele-when-we-were-young-second-single-25|journal=Billboard|date=14 December 2015|accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> The song was released on 22 January 2016, eventually peaking at number 14 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele \u2013 When We Were Young|url=http://www.earone.it/news/adele_when_we_were_young_radio_date_22_01_2016_17494743/|publisher=EarOne.it|accessdate=15 January 2016|date=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[iHeartRadio]] reported on 27 April 2016 that \"[[Send My Love (To Your New Lover)]]\" had been selected as the album's third single and that it would be serviced to radio stations on 17 May 2016. The song peaked at No. 8 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 in the United States, No. 5 in the UK and No. 10 in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 40/Mainstream Future Releases|url=http://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|publisher=All Access|accessdate=9 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509210141/http://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|archivedate=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 November 2016, \"[[Water Under the Bridge (song)|Water Under the Bridge]]\" was released as the fourth single from the album. The single peaked at No. 26 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 in the United States, No. 39 on the UK Singles Chart and No. 37 on the Canadian Hot 100.\n\n=== Touring ===\n{{Main|Adele Live 2016}}\n\nAdele embarked on her third concert tour titled [[Adele Live 2016]], which ran from February to November 2016. The first leg started in [[Belfast]] on 29 February 2016 in the [[SSE Arena, Belfast|SSE Arena]] before moving throughout mainland Europe and concluding in [[Antwerp]] at [[Sportpaleis]] on 15 June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-34934518|title=Adele announces first tour since 2011|work=BBC News}}</ref> The second leg began on 5 July at the [[Xcel Energy Center]] in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]], Minnesota and continues throughout the United States and Canada with multiple dates at each venue. The tour concluded on 2 July 2017 in London, UK. Demand for the tour was extremely high and all shows sold out within minutes of going on sale. Over 500,000 fans registered at Adele.com to purchase tickets, with 57,000 tickets sold for the 12 shows that were put on sale in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele's Ticket Sales Strategy, Looking to Stop Scalpers, Draws Criticism (and a Lot of Fans)|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6784895/adele-tickets-security-stubhub-scalpers|work=Billboard|accessdate=3 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 6.8/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/7668/Adele-25.aspx|title=25 by Adele reviews|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n| MC = 75/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/25/adele|title=Reviews for 25 by Adele|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/25-mw0002828987|title=25 \u2013 Adele|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=9 December 2015}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"dailytele\">{{cite web|last=McCormick|first=Neil|authorlink=Neil McCormick|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/adele-25-review/|title=Adele, 25, album review: 'pop doesn't come more perfect than this'|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=18 November 2015|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = A\u2212<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web|last=Greenblatt|first=Leah|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/11/19/adele-25-ew-review|title=25 by Adele: EW Review|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=19 November 2015|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"guardianreview\">{{cite news|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|authorlink=Alexis Petridis|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/nov/19/adele-25-album-review|title=Adele: 25 review \u2013 'We've been here before,' she sings. And she's right|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=19 November 2015|accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"indereview\">{{cite news|last=Gill|first=Andy|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/adele-new-album-review-adele-arrives-to-save-the-music-industry-with-25-a6739231.html|title=Adele 25 review: New album arrives to save the music industry|work=[[The Independent]]|date=18 November 2015|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 3/5<ref name=\"nme\">{{cite web|last=Cooper|first=Leonie|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/adele/16341|title=Adele \u2013 '25'|work=[[NME]]|date=18 November 2015|accessdate=19 November 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119152315/http://www.nme.com/reviews/adele/16341|archivedate=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 7.3/10<ref name=Pitchfork>{{cite web|last=Petrusich|first=Amanda|authorlink=Amanda Petrusich|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21246-25/|title=Adele: 25|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=23 November 2015|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone review\">{{cite web|last=Dolan|first=Jon|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/adele-25-20151124|title=25|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=23 November 2015|accessdate=23 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = 6/10<ref name=\"Spin Magazine Review\">{{cite web|last=Rachel|first=T. Cole|url=http://www.spin.com/2015/11/review-adele-25/|title=Review: Age Ain't Nothing But a Bummer for Adele on '25'|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=23 November 2015|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Gardner|first=Elysa|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/11/19/album-of-the-week-review-adele-25/75672282/|title=Adele rolls in deeper on her new album, '25'|work=[[USA Today]]|date=20 November 2015|accessdate=23 October 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''25'' received generally positive reviews from critics. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized rating]] out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 75, based on 35 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/> Bruce Handy, writing a review for ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'', regarded the music as traditional [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] and modern [[pop music]], with songs that are mostly [[ballad]]s.<ref name=\"Vanity Fair Review\">{{cite journal|first=Bruce|last=Handy|title=Review: Adele's ''25'' Is the Confessional Blockbuster You Wanted It to Be|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2015/11/review-adele-25-album|journal=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=21 November 2015|date=20 November 2015}}</ref> Reviewing for [[AllMusic]], [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] comments, \"Fittingly, ''25'' also plays better over the long haul, its march of slow songs steadily revealing subtle emotional or musical distinctions\", where \"all 11 songs are&nbsp;... a piece&nbsp;... [of] shaded melancholy gaining most of their power through performance\", and arguing that the \"cohesive sound only accentuates how Adele has definitively claimed this arena of dignified heartbreak as her own\".<ref name=\"AllMusic\" /> [[Neil McCormick]] from ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' stated that the album, covered the same \"musical and emotional terrain\" as ''21'' and continued to call it an \"equal of its predecessor.\"<ref name=\"dailytele\"/> Jon Dolan of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' commented that the album's \"nostalgic mood is the perfect fit for an artist who reaches back decades for her influences, even as her all-or-nothing urgency feels utterly modern\" and also praising her \"incredible phrasing \u2013 the way she can infuse any line with nuance and power\", which he argued served as \"more proof that she's among the greatest interpreters of romantic lyrics\".<ref name=\"Rolling Stone review\" /> Leah Greenblatt of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called it \"a record that feels both new and familiar\u2014a beautiful if safe collection of panoramic ballads and prettily executed detours\".<ref name=\"EW\"/> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' praised Adele's vocal performance writing that it's \"swathed in echo, sounding like she's wailing beneath the vaults of the planet's most cavernous cathedral, they hit hard.\"<ref name=\"Rosen\">{{cite journal|last=Rosen|first=Jody|authorlink=Jody Rosen|date=19 November 2015|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/review/6769956/adele-25-album-review|title=Adele Powers Through a Lifetime of Regret & Weariness on '25' Album Review|journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> [[Amanda Petrusich]] from ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' praised Adele's vocal delivery, arguing that \"[her] instincts as a singer remain unmatched; she is, inarguably, the greatest vocalist of her generation, an artist who instinctively understands timbre and pitch, when to let some air in\".<ref name=Pitchfork/>\n\nIn a less enthusiastic review for ''[[The Independent]]'', Andy Gill said the songs \"River Lea\" and \"Send My Love (To Your New Lover)\" were \"isolated moments of musical intrigue scattered here and there through the album\", which he said gradually became \"swamped by the kind of dreary piano ballads that are Adele's fall-back position\".<ref name=\"indereview\"/> Leonie Cooper from ''[[NME]]'' felt Adele and her team of songwriters/producers did not take any risks musically, instead \"following a formula that has so far resulted in 30 million [[album sales]]\".<ref name=\"nme\" /> [[Jude Rogers]] found the ''25'' bogged down by the emotionally weighty themes of Adele's previous records, comparing the singer to \"a friend who you\u2019ve helped countless times but who won\u2019t listen, who actually enjoys being in a mess, whose sparkle gets dampened \u2013 gets drowned \u2013 as a consequence\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Rodgers|first=Jude|authorlink=Jude Rodgers|date=20 November 2015|url=http://thequietus.com/articles/19275-adele-25-review|title=Adele|work=[[The Quietus]]|accessdate=31 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Year end lists ===\n''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine ranked the album at number two on its \"The 50 Best Albums of 2015\" year-end list.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-albums-of-2015-20151201/adele-25-20151130|title=The 50 Best Albums of 2015|work=Rolling Stone|date=1 December 2015|accessdate=1 December 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151203182247/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/50-best-albums-of-2015-20151201/adele-25-20151130 |archivedate=3 December 2015}}</ref> American newspaper ''[[Newsday]]'' also ranked the album at number two on their list of 2015's best albums,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/best-albums-of-2015-1.10156232|title=Best albums of 2015|work=[[Newsday]]|first=Glenn|last=Gamboa|date=14 December 2015|accessdate=20 December 2015}}</ref> UK publication ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'' listed the album at number four on their list of The Best Albums of 2015<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/best-albums-of-2015|title=The Best Albums of 2015|work=Complex|date=1 December 2015|accessdate=24 December 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205101722/http://www.complex.com/music/best-albums-of-2015/|archivedate=5 December 2015}}</ref> and ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' listed the album at number three.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/gallery/best-albums-2015/?slide=224843#224843|title=The 40 Best Albums of 2015|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n\nAt the [[2016 BRIT Awards]], Adele was nominated for five awards, in which she won four including [[Brit Award for British Album of the Year|British Album of the Year]] for ''25'' and [[Brit Award for British Single of the Year|British Single of the Year]] for \"Hello\".<ref name=\"McGeorge 2016\">{{cite web|last=McGeorge|first=Alistair|title=Who won BRIT Awards 2016 Album of the Year?|website=mirror|date=24 February 2016|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/adele-wins-brit-awards-2016-7432961|accessdate=24 February 2016 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190112081339/https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/adele-wins-brit-awards-2016-7432961 |archivedate=12 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Horton 2016\">{{cite web|last=Horton|first=Helena|title=Brits 2016: 'I didn't get cut off and I didn't swear' emotional Adele accepts fourth Brit award for Best Album|website=The Daily Telegraph|date=24 February 2016|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/news/adele-expected-to-win-top-award-at-the-brits/|accessdate=24 February 2016 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181117062927/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/news/adele-expected-to-win-top-award-at-the-brits/ |archivedate=17 November 2018}}</ref> At the [[2016 Billboard Music Awards|2016 ''Billboard'' Music Awards]], the singer was nominated for nine categories, winning five, including [[Billboard Music Award for Top Billboard 200 Album|Top Billboard 200 Album]] for ''25'' and [[Billboard Music Award for Top Selling Song|Top Selling Song]] for \"Hello\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/7378353/billboard-music-awards-2016-complete-winners-list|title=Billboard Music Awards 2016: Complete Winners List|work=Billboard|date=22 May 2016|accessdate=22 May 2016 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119051414/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/7378353/billboard-music-awards-2016-complete-winners-list |archivedate=19 January 2019}}</ref> At the [[Juno Awards of 2016|2016 Juno Awards]], Adele won [[Juno Award for International Album of the Year|International Album of the Year]] for ''25'' and [[Juno Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]] for \"Hello\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://junoawards.ca/nomination/2016-international-album-of-the-year-adele/|title=03 \u2013 2016 \u2013 INTERNATIONAL ALBUM OF THE YEAR \u2013 Adele \u2013 The JUNO Awards |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116065801/http://junoawards.ca/nomination/2016-international-album-of-the-year-adele/ |archivedate=16 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://junoawards.ca/nomination/2016-video-of-the-year-xavier-dolan/|title=38 \u2013 2016 \u2013 VIDEO OF THE YEAR \u2013 Adele \u2013 The JUNO Awards |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420032935/https://junoawards.ca/nomination/2016-video-of-the-year-xavier-dolan/ |archivedate=20 April 2016}}</ref> Adele also won ''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]''{{'}}s Album of the Year for ''25''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://attitude.co.uk/attitudes-british-album-of-the-year-adele-25/|title=Attitude's British Album of the Year: Adele, '25' |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012151316/http://attitude.co.uk/attitudes-british-album-of-the-year-adele-25/ |archivedate=12 October 2016}}</ref> At the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards|59th Grammy Awards]], ''25'' won six Grammy: [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]], while \"Hello\" won [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]]. Adele became the first artist in history to win all three general field awards in the same ceremony twice, previously winning all three categories in [[54th Annual Grammy Awards|2012]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/beyonc%C3%A9-alison-krauss-9-times-women-made-grammy-history|title=9 Times Women Made Grammy History|work=[Grammy.com]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326172913/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/beyonc%C3%A9-alison-krauss-9-times-women-made-grammy-history|archivedate=26 March 2018}}</ref> Her producer, [[Greg Kurstin]] won [[Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Non-Classical|Producer of the Year, Non-Classical]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/59th-annual-grammy-awards|title=59th Annual Grammy Awards|work=[Grammy.com]|date=12 February 2017|accessdate=12 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226223537/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/59th-annual-grammy-awards |archivedate=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width: 60%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Ceremony\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" scope=\"row\" | 2015\n| [[Gaffa (magazine)#GAFFA Awards|GAFFA Awards]]\n| Best Foreign Album\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"1\"|<ref>{{cite web |title=GAFFA-Prisen \u2013 og vinderne er... |url=https://gaffa.dk/nyhed/101913/gaffa-prisen-og-vinderne-er/ |website=[[Gaffa (magazine)|Gaffa]] |accessdate=September 1, 2019 |language=Danish}}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"9\" scope=\"row\" | 2016\n| [[American Music Awards]]\n| [[American Music Award for Favorite Pop/Rock Album|Favorite Pop/Rock Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theamas.com/2016/10/the-2016-american-music-awards-nominations-announced/ |title=The 2016 American Music Awards Nominations Announced |publisher=AMA |date=10 October 2016 |accessdate=10 October 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010201107/http://www.theamas.com/2016/10/the-2016-american-music-awards-nominations-announced/ |archivedate=10 October 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[BBC Music Awards]]\n| BBC Radio Album of the Year\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/articles/0242a2af-6f63-43b0-90e5-54fead8d55c9 |title=BBC Music Awards 2016&nbsp;\u2013 The Nominees |publisher=BBC |accessdate=6 December 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205181110/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/articles/0242a2af-6f63-43b0-90e5-54fead8d55c9 |archivedate= 5 December 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Billboard Music Awards]]\n| [[Billboard Music Award for Top Billboard 200 Album|Top Billboard 200 Album]]\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/7378353/billboard-music-awards-2016-complete-winners-list |title=Billboard Music Awards 2016: Complete Winners List |work=Billboard |accessdate=23 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524230951/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bbma/7378353/billboard-music-awards-2016-complete-winners-list |archivedate=24 May 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Brit Awards]]\n|[[Brit Award for British Album of the Year|British Album of the Year]]\n|{{Won}}\n|rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref name=\"McGeorge 2016\"/>\n|-\n| [[Danish Music Awards]]\n| International Album of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>https://genius.com/Danish-music-awards-de-nominerede-2016-lyrics</ref>\n|-\n| [[Echo Music Prize|ECHO Music Awards]]\n| Album of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=10 March 2016 |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/adele-tops-noms-germany-s-874167 |title=Adele Tops Noms for Germany's Echo Music Awards |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=10 March 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311110014/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/adele-tops-noms-germany-s-874167 |archivedate=11 March 2016 }}</ref><br/><ref>{{cite news|accessdate=8 April 2016 |url=http://www.echopop.de/fileadmin/echopop/upload/news/2016/PM_8_ECHO_2016_Gewinner.pdf |title=ECHO 2016: Vier Preise f\u00fcr Helene Fischer |work=ECHO Deutsche Musikpreis |date=7 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413133053/http://www.echopop.de/fileadmin/echopop/upload/news/2016/PM_8_ECHO_2016_Gewinner.pdf |archivedate=13 April 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[iHeartRadio Music Awards]]\n| Album of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"1\"|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/taylor-swift-the-weeknd-lead-iheartradio-music-awards-noms-20160209 |title=Taylor Swift, the Weeknd Lead iHeartRadio Music Awards Noms |work=Rolling Stone |date=9 February 2016 |accessdate=10 February 2016 |author=Blistein, Jon |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160210093249/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/taylor-swift-the-weeknd-lead-iheartradio-music-awards-noms-20160209 |archivedate=10 February 2016}}</ref><br><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.iheart.com/features/iheartradio-music-awards-15/articles/15/490103/surprise-announcement-adele-accepts-song-of-14552999/ |title=Surprise Announcement! Adele Accepts Song Of The Year iHeartRadio Music Award In The Middle Of Her Concert |publisher=[[iHeartMedia]] |date=31 March 2016 |accessdate=31 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406072716/http://news.iheart.com/features/iheartradio-music-awards-15/articles/15/490103/surprise-announcement-adele-accepts-song-of-14552999/ |archivedate=6 April 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Juno Awards]]\n|[[Juno Award for International Album of the Year|International Album of the Year]]\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"1\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://junoawards.ca/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-Gala-Dinners-Awards-Winners-List.pdf |title=2016 JUNO Gala Dinner & Awards Winners |work=JUNO Awards |date=3 April 2016 |accessdate=3 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415101905/http://junoawards.ca/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/2016-Gala-Dinners-Awards-Winners-List.pdf |archivedate=15 April 2016 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Los Premios 40 Principales]]\n| [[Premios 40 Principales for Best International Album|International Album of the Year]]\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://los40.com/especiales/los40-music-awards/2016/nominados/ |title=LOS40 Music Awards 2016: Nominados |language=Spanish |publisher=[[Los 40 Principales]] |date=6 October 2016 |accessdate=11 October 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011231149/http://los40.com/especiales/los40-music-awards/2016/nominados/ |archivedate=11 October 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" scope=\"row\" | 2017\n| [[iHeartRadio Music Awards]]\n| Best Pop Album\n| {{won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=1|<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.iheart.com/news/heres-the-complete-list-of-iheartradio-15616268/ |first=Isha |last=Thorpe |publisher=iHeartMedia |title=Here's The Complete List Of #iHeartAwards Winners |date=5 March 2017 |accessdate=5 March 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170409080744/https://www.iheart.com/news/heres-the-complete-list-of-iheartradio-15616268/ |archivedate=9 April 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Grammy Awards]]\n| [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite news|accessdate=6 December 2016 |url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees |title=59TH ANNUAL GRAMMY AWARDS NOMINEES |work=The Recording Academy |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131073014/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/59th-annual-grammy-awards |archivedate= 31 January 2018 }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Album]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n== Commercial performance ==\n\n=== Europe ===\nIn the United Kingdom, ''25'' debuted at number one on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and sold 800,307 copies in its first chart week, overtaking [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]' ''[[Be Here Now (album)|Be Here Now]]'' (1997) to become the [[List of fastest-selling albums|fastest-selling album]] of all time in the UK.<ref name=\"OCC week 1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/adele-s-25-is-officially-the-uk-s-biggest-selling-number-1-album-ever__12416/|title=Adele's 25 is officially the UK's biggest selling Number 1 album ever|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=27 November 2015|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=27 November 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116092558/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/adele-s-25-is-officially-the-uk-s-biggest-selling-number-1-album-ever__12416/ |archivedate=16 November 2018}}</ref> Of that total, 252,423 copies were digital downloads, breaking the record for most digital copies sold in a week, and 548,000 were physical copies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele's '25' Sets Biggest U.K. Opening Sales Week, Most Downloaded No. 1 Album|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6777865/adele-25-sets-biggest-uk-opening-sales-week-most-downloaded-no-1-xl-recordings-official-charts-company|website=Billboard|accessdate=27 November 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211014137/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6777865/adele-25-sets-biggest-uk-opening-sales-week-most-downloaded-no-1-xl-recordings-official-charts-company |archivedate=11 December 2018}}</ref> In its first week, ''25'' sold more copies in the UK than the combined sales of the last 19 number-one albums in UK on their debut week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34948022|title=Adele's 25 makes UK chart history with 800,000 album sales|work=BBC News |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181011115004/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34948022 |archivedate=11 October 2018}}</ref> It also outsold that week's other 86 highest-selling albums combined.<ref name=\"OCC week 1\" /> After ten days on sale, it became the fastest million-seller in the UK, surpassing ''Be Here Now'', which achieved this feat in 17 days in 1997.<ref name=\"1 million in UK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/overnight-news-from-around-the-world-89/063519|title=Adele's 25 enters record books for fastest million seller in the UK|work=Music Week|date=30 November 2015|first=Tom|last=Pakinkis|accessdate=30 November 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116112748/http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/overnight-news-from-around-the-world-89/063519 |archivedate=16 November 2018}}</ref> In its second week, ''25'' sold 439,337 copies, which broke the record for highest second-week sales in the UK and also was the sixth biggest weekly sales of all time.<ref name=\"uksales2ndweek\">{{cite news|url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/adele-breaks-uk-record-for-biggest-second-week-album-sales/063579|title=Adele breaks UK record for biggest second week album sales|last=Jones|first=Alan|date=4 December 2015|work=[[Music Week]]|accessdate=4 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116115242/http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/adele-breaks-uk-record-for-biggest-second-week-album-sales/063579 |archivedate=16 November 2018}}</ref> In its third week, ''25'' sold 354,000 copies, which represents the second highest third-week sales since [[Take That]]'s ''[[The Circus (Take That album)|The Circus]]'', which sold 382,000 copies in its third week,<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele beats Coldplay to Number 1 on the Official Albums Chart|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/adeles-25-beats-coldplays-a-head-full-of-dreams-to-number-1-on-the-official-albums-chart__13161/|publisher=officialcharts.com|accessdate=11 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306190106/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/adeles-25-beats-coldplays-a-head-full-of-dreams-to-number-1-on-the-official-albums-chart__13161/ |archivedate=6 March 2019}}</ref> and was also certified quintuple platinum by the [[British Phonographic Industry]], with total UK sales at 1,593,530 copies.<ref name=\"third week sales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/businessanalysis/read/official-charts-analysis-adele-beats-coldplay/063634|title=Official Charts Analysis: Adele beats Coldplay|last=Jones|first=Alan|date=11 December 2015|work=[[Music Week]]|accessdate=11 December 2015|url-access=subscription  }}{{dead link|date=July 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> On 18 December 29 days after its release, the album surpassed sales of 2 million copies in the UK, becoming the fastest 2 million-seller in the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/adele-s-25-becomes-the-fastest-2-million-selling-album-in-uk-chart-history__13224/|title=Adele's 25 becomes the fastest 2 million-selling album in UK chart history|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=18 December 2015|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=18 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116100101/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/adele-s-25-becomes-the-fastest-2-million-selling-album-in-uk-chart-history__13224/ |archivedate=16 November 2018}}</ref> In its fifth week of release, the album sold another 450,000 copies in the UK, becoming the Christmas number one.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele scores the biggest selling album of Christmas 2015|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/adele-scores-the-biggest-selling-album-of-christmas-2015__13261/|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=25 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116090507/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/adele-scores-the-biggest-selling-album-of-christmas-2015__13261/ |archivedate=16 November 2018}}</ref> The album has spent 13 non-consecutive weeks at number one<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/adele-says-hello-to-number-1-again-after-headlining-glastonbury__15539/|title=Adele says Hello to Number 1 again after headlining Glastonbury|last=Myers|first=Justin|date=1 July 2016|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=2 July 2016 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116090651/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/adele-says-hello-to-number-1-again-after-headlining-glastonbury__15539/ |archivedate=16 November 2018}}</ref> and, as of November 2016, had sold 3.12 million copies, being later certified 11\u00d7 Platinum.<ref name=\"bpi\" /><ref name=\"November UK sales\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/adeles-25-one-year-on__17207/|title=Adele's 25 one year on: 14 incredible chart facts|last=Myers|first=Justin|date=26 November 2016|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=26 November 2016 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116095931/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/adeles-25-one-year-on__17207/ |archivedate=16 November 2018}}</ref> In December 2016, it became only the third album to be the UK's biggest-seller two years in a row, after [[Simon & Garfunkel]]'s ''[[Bridge over Troubled Water]]'' (1970 and 1971) and [[Simply Red]]'s ''[[Stars (Simply Red album)|Stars]]'' (1991 and 1992).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.musicweek.com/analysis/read/official-charts-analysis-little-mix-return-to-albums-summit/067017|title=Official Charts Analysis: Little Mix return to albums summit|last=Jones|first=Alan|date=30 December 2016|work=[[Music Week]]|accessdate=30 December 2016|url-access=subscription  |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116113342/http://www.musicweek.com/analysis/read/official-charts-analysis-little-mix-return-to-albums-summit/067017 |archivedate=16 November 2018}}</ref> It has sold over 3.50&nbsp;million copies as of October 2018, making the ten biggest selling studio album in the UK history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-uks-biggest-studio-albums-of-all-time__24431/|title=The UK's biggest studio albums of all time|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=13 October 2018|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=13 October 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107091751/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-uks-biggest-studio-albums-of-all-time__24431/ |archivedate=7 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nElsewhere in Europe, ''25'' also opened atop of the German charts after selling 263,000 units, the largest weekly sale for a record since [[Herbert Gr\u00f6nemeyer]]'s 2007 release ''[[12 (Herbert Gr\u00f6nemeyer album)|12]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Neues Album \"25\": Adele gelingt das Triple in Deutschland|url=http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/musik/adele-und-25-bester-albumstart-in-deutschland-seit-acht-jahren-a-1064966.html|work=Der Spiegel|accessdate=27 November 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118104018/http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/musik/adele-und-25-bester-albumstart-in-deutschland-seit-acht-jahren-a-1064966.html |archivedate=18 November 2017}}</ref> In France, ''25'' became the fastest-selling album of 2015 after it sold 169,693 copies, of which 26,295 were downloads.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele : \"25\" num\u00e9ro un des ventes en France. Un d\u00e9marrage spectaculaire !|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Adele/news-99911.html|website=Charts in France|accessdate=27 November 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813111432/http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Adele/news-99911.html |archivedate=13 August 2018}}</ref> The album sold another 129,200 copies in France in its second week, bringing its two-week total to 300,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top Albums : Adele r\u00e9siste remarquablement, Fr\u00e9ro Delavega plus fort que Patrick Bruel|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/actualite/news-100097.html|publisher=chartsinfrance.net|accessdate=8 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116055349/http://www.chartsinfrance.net/actualite/news-100097.html |archivedate=16 November 2018}}</ref> In its third week, ''25''<nowiki/>'s sales rose to 132,200 copies in France, bringing its total sales to 430,000 copies, which made it the third best-selling album of the year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top Albums : Adele toujours loin devant, Jul \u00e9crase Coldplay, Booba et Rohff|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/actualite/news-100191.html|publisher=chartsinfrance.net|accessdate=16 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116055317/http://www.chartsinfrance.net/actualite/news-100191.html |archivedate=16 November 2018}}</ref> In its fourth week of sales in France, sales of the album further rose to 133,000 copies, bringing its total sales to 565,000 copies in the country, earning it a diamond certification there.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Adele/news-100280.html|title=Charts in France |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813112428/http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Adele/news-100280.html |archivedate=13 August 2018}}</ref> In the Netherlands, the album debuted at number one with first week sales of over 120,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele verslaat Marco Borsato in Album Top 100|url=http://megatop50.3fm.nl/nieuws/detail/349843/adele-verslaat-marco-borsato-in-album-top-100|website=Mega Top 50|accessdate=29 November 2015 }}{{dead link|date=July 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The album also sold over 180,000 copies in the [[Benelux]] in its first week of release.<ref>{{cite web|title=Industrie levert 200.000 fysieke cd's Adele en Marco Borsato uit {{!}} Nieuws {{!}} Entertainment Business|url = http://www.entertainmentbusiness.nl/nieuws/2015-W47/industrie-levert-200000-fysieke-cds-adele-marco-borsato-uit|website = www.entertainmentbusiness.nl|accessdate = 5 December 2015 }}</ref> In Spain, the album debuted atop the charts selling 20,000 copies in its first week,<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele agota entradas para sus dos conciertos en Barcelona \u2013 20minutos.es|url=http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/2620203/0/adele-concierto-barcelona/entradas-agotadas/nueva-fecha/|website=20minutos.es \u2013 \u00daltimas Noticias|accessdate=5 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116032541/https://www.20minutos.es/noticia/2620203/0/adele-concierto-barcelona/entradas-agotadas/nueva-fecha/ |archivedate=16 November 2018}}</ref> while in Portugal it also debuted at number one with sales of 3,200 copies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele: 25 vendeu 3 mil e 200 c\u00f3pias na primeira semana em Portugal|url=https://blitz.sapo.pt/adele-i25i-vendeu-3-mil-e-200-copias-na-primeira-semana-em-portugal=f98803|website=BLITZ|accessdate=5 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190318171329/https://blitz.pt/principal/update/adele-i25i-vendeu-3-mil-e-200-copias-na-primeira-semana-em-portugal=f98803 |archivedate=18 March 2019}}</ref> ''25'' also entered the charts at number one in Switzerland, selling over 40,000 copies in its first week, receiving a double platinum certification there.<ref>{{cite web|title=20 Minuten \u2013 Adele nimmt Kurs auf Schweizer Allzeitrekord \u2013 Musik|url=http://www.20min.ch/entertainment/musik/story/Adele-nimmt-Kurs-auf-Schweizer-Allzeitrekord-25623986|website=20 Minuten|accessdate=5 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813111736/https://www.20min.ch/entertainment/musik/story/Adele-nimmt-Kurs-auf-Schweizer-Allzeitrekord-25623986 |archivedate=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== North America ===\nIn the United States, ''25'' sold 2.3 million after three days of availability, becoming the fastest-selling album of the 21st century and the best-selling album of 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6770443/adeles-25-two-million-first-three-days|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|title=Adele's '25' Sells 2.3 Million in First Three Days in U.S., Aiming for 2.9 Million Debut Week|work=Billboard|date=23 November 2015|accessdate=23 November 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308082435/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6770443/adeles-25-two-million-first-three-days |archivedate=8 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6770470/adele-25-already-2015-biggest-selling-album|title=Adele's '25' Is Already 2015's Biggest-Selling Album|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=23 November 2015|work=Billboard|accessdate=24 November 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190302210428/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6770470/adele-25-already-2015-biggest-selling-album |archivedate=2 March 2019}}</ref> The album reached sales of 2.433 million early on its fourth day, surpassing the single-week record for an album since [[Nielsen Soundscan]] began tracking sales in 1991, set by [[NSYNC]]'s ''[[No Strings Attached (NSYNC album)|No Strings Attached]]'' in March 2000 when it debuted with 2.416 million copies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Official: Adele Breaks *NSYNC's Single-Week U.S. Album Sales Record|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6776941/adele-breaks-album-sales-record-single-week-nsync|website=Billboard|accessdate=24 November 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181224190907/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6776941/adele-breaks-album-sales-record-single-week-nsync |archivedate=24 December 2018}}</ref> In total, it sold 3.38 million copies in the US in its first week, becoming the first album ever to sell over 3 million copies in a week.<ref name=\"usdebut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6777905/adele-25-sales-first-week-us|title=Adele's '25' Official First Week U.S. Sales: 3.38 Million|work=Billboard|date=28 November 2015|accessdate=28 November 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127071838/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6777905/adele-25-sales-first-week-us |archivedate=27 November 2018}}</ref> The album earned 3.48 million [[album-equivalent unit]]s in the US in its first week of release, which is the largest registered figure since the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] began tracking weekly popularity based on overall units in December 2014. ''25'' also achieved 96,000 in track-equivalent album units in the US in its debut week, and another 8,000 in streaming-equivalent album units, all of which came from streams of the single \"Hello\", as it was the only song from the album available on streaming services.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele's '25' Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart, '21' Returns to Top 10|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6777926/adele-25-debuts-no-1-billboard-200-albums-chart|website=Billboard|accessdate=29 November 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118134036/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6777926/adele-25-debuts-no-1-billboard-200-albums-chart |archivedate=18 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the first three days of its second week, ''25'' sold over 650,000 units, surpassing 4 million sales, ending the week with 1.11 million copies.<ref name=\"us4mil\">{{cite web|title=Adele's '25' Sales Rise to Over 4 Million in U.S.|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6778038/adele-25-sales-4-million|website=Billboard|accessdate=1 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181222094603/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6778038/adele-25-sales-4-million |archivedate=22 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Adele's '25' Sells 1.11 Million in Second Week in U.S.|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6785931/adele-25-second-week-sales-us|website=Billboard|accessdate=6 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118101548/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6785931/adele-25-second-week-sales-us |archivedate=18 November 2018}}</ref> In its third full week, the album sold 695,000 copies, surpassing 5 million sales, becoming the first album to do so in a calendar year since Adele's own album ''[[21 (Adele album)|21]]'' in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele's '25' Hits 5 Million Sold in U.S.|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6805295/adele-25-5-million-sold|website=Billboard|accessdate=10 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190310162817/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6805295/adele-25-5-million-sold |archivedate=10 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Billboard 200: Adele's '25' Rules for Third Week at No. 1, Coldplay Debuts at No. 2 {{!}} Billboard|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6805727/adeles-25-no-1-on-billboard-200-album-chart-third-week-coldplay-a-head-full-of-dreams|work= Billboard|accessdate = 13 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305044855/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6805727/adeles-25-no-1-on-billboard-200-album-chart-third-week-coldplay-a-head-full-of-dreams |archivedate=5 March 2019}}</ref> By its fourth week sale of 790,000 copies, ''25'' became the best-selling album in any calendar year since [[Usher (singer)|Usher]] sold 7.98 million in 2004 with ''[[Confessions (Usher album)|Confessions]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele's '25' Biggest-Selling Album Released Since 2011, Spends Fourth Week at No. 1 |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6813934/adele-25-billboard-200-biggest-selling-album-since-2011 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190305062057/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6813934/adele-25-billboard-200-biggest-selling-album-since-2011 |archivedate=5 March 2019}}</ref> It sold 1.16 million copies in pure album sales in its fifth week, and became the first album to sell over one million copies in three different frames.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele's '25' Sells Another 1.16 Million in U.S., Spends Fifth Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6821619/adele-25-billboard-200-fifth-week-sells-another-million|website=Billboard|date=27 December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015|author=Caulfield, Keith |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211021152/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6821619/adele-25-billboard-200-fifth-week-sells-another-million |archivedate=11 December 2018}}</ref> In its sixth week, the album sold another 307,000 copies at number one on the ''Billboard'' 200, becoming the first album to sell over 300,000 copies in consecutive six weeks since 2001 when [[Creed (band)|Creed]] did so with ''[[Weathered]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele's '25' Scores Sixth Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6828916/adele-25-sixth-week-no-1-billboard-200|work=Billboard|accessdate=4 January 2016 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181220121218/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6828916/adele-25-sixth-week-no-1-billboard-200 |archivedate=20 December 2018}}</ref> By the end of 2015, ''25'' had sold a total of 8,008,000 equivalent album units, 7,441,000 of which were pure album sales. It also sold 2,310,000 digital copies by the year end, making it the third best-selling digital album of all time behind Adele's own ''21'' and [[Taylor Swift]]'s ''[[1989 (Taylor Swift album)|1989]]''. ''25'' was also the second biggest-selling album of a calendar year by a female artist in Nielsen history, only trailing behind [[Britney Spears]]' ''[[Oops!... I Did It Again (album)|Oops!... I Did It Again]]'' which sold 7,890,000 copies in 2000.<ref name=\"caulfield1\">{{cite news|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|title=Adele's '25' Rules as Nielsen Music's Top Album of 2015 in U.S.|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6835248/adele-25-top-album-of-2015-in-us|date=5 January 2016|accessdate=6 January 2016 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820120850/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6835248/adele-25-top-album-of-2015-in-us |archivedate=20 August 2018}}</ref> In its seventh week, the album remained at number one, selling another 164,000 units, becoming the first album by a female artist to top the ''Billboard'' 200 in its first seven weeks since [[Whitney Houston]]'s 1987 album ''[[Whitney (album)|Whitney]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele's '25' Still No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart, Rachel Platten Bows in Top Five {{!}} Billboard|url = http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6836462/adele-25-no-1-billboard-200-rachel-platten-wildfire|website = Billboard|access-date = 11 January 2016 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102205733/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6836462/adele-25-no-1-billboard-200-rachel-platten-wildfire |archivedate=2 January 2019}}</ref> In total, the album has spent ten non-consecutive weeks at the top of the chart, becoming the fifth album released since the 2000 to achieve, at least, 10 weeks at the summit.<ref>{{cite news|first=Keith|last=Caulfield|title=Adele's '25' Scores 10th Week at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Chart|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6890511/adele-25-scores-10th-week-at-no-1-on-billboard-200-chart|work=Billboard|date=28 February 2016|accessdate=28 February 2016 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211012551/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6890511/adele-25-scores-10th-week-at-no-1-on-billboard-200-chart |archivedate=11 December 2018}}</ref> In the year of 2016, it sold 2.37 million copies and equivalent units, of which 1.7 million were pure sales, ranking as the best-selling album of the year in pure sales and second best including equivalent albums.<ref name=bb2016nielsen>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7647018/drake-views-nielsen-music-top-album-2016-us|last=Caufield|first=Keith|title=Drake's 'Views' Is Nielsen Music's Top Album of 2016 in the U.S.|date=5 January 2017|work=Billboard|accessdate=5 January 2017 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190307062847/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7647018/drake-views-nielsen-music-top-album-2016-us |archivedate=7 March 2019}}</ref> As of March 2018, ''25'' has sold 9.45&nbsp;million copies in pure sales.<ref name=\"ussales\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8257460/taylor-swift-reputation-sells-two-million|title=Taylor Swift's 'Reputation' Becomes Only Album Released in Last Two Years to Sell 2 Million Copies in U.S.|magazine=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=21 March 2018|accessdate=31 May 2018 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213192713/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8257460/taylor-swift-reputation-sells-two-million |archivedate=13 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn Canada, the album debuted at number one with sales of 306,000 copies, breaking the record for highest first-week sales, which was previously held by [[Celine Dion]]'s ''[[Let's Talk About Love]]'', which had sold 230,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele Becomes First Act Ever To Sell 1&nbsp;m in Two Separate Weeks|url=http://www.noise11.com/news/music-news-adele-becomes-first-act-ever-to-sell-1m-in-two-separate-weeks-20151205|publisher=Noise11.com|accessdate=5 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308080818/http://www.noise11.com/news/music-news-adele-becomes-first-act-ever-to-sell-1m-in-two-separate-weeks-20151205 |archivedate=8 March 2019}}</ref> In its second week ''25'' sold another 145,000 copies in Canada, bringing its two-week total to 451,000 copies. This represents the eighth-highest weekly sales in Canada, as well as the second highest second-week sales for an album, just behind the 146,000 copies sold by the Canadian compilation ''[[Big Shiny Tunes 2]]'' in its second week in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/67270545/Canadian%20Newsletters/2015/nielsen_music_canadian_update_Dec07_2015.pdf|title=Adele's 25 Reign|accessdate=15 December 2015|publisher=Nielsen SoundScan Canada|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151208125112/https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/67270545/Canadian%20Newsletters/2015/nielsen_music_canadian_update_Dec07_2015.pdf|archive-date = 8 December 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> The album sold 1 million copies in the nation by May 2016.<ref name=\"cantotal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fyimusicnews.ca/articles/2016/04/27/adeles-25-has-now-sold-1m-copies-canada|title=Adele's 25 Has Now Sold 1&nbsp;m Copies in Canada|publisher=FYI Music|date=3 May 2016|last=Cross|first=Alan|accessdate=3 May 2016 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830110132/https://www.fyimusicnews.ca/articles/2016/04/27/adeles-25-has-now-sold-1m-copies-canada |archivedate=30 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Oceania and South Africa ===\nIn Australia, the album sold more than 210,000 copies in five days, passing the triple platinum mark there.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele's 25 hits triple platinum in australia|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2015/11/adele-25-hits-triple-platinum-in-australia/|website=auspOp|accessdate=25 November 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405213043/https://www.auspop.com.au/2015/11/adele-25-hits-triple-platinum-in-australia/ |archivedate=5 April 2019}}</ref> It was the best-selling album of both 2015 and 2016,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Top-selling albums, singles of 2016: Adele is bigger than Christmas|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/topselling-albums-singles-of-2016-adele-is-bigger-than-christmas-20170105-gtmdhf.html|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=6 January 2017|accessdate=30 January 2017 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105203926/https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/topselling-albums-singles-of-2016-adele-is-bigger-than-christmas-20170105-gtmdhf.html |archivedate=5 January 2017}}</ref> and achieved decuple platinum certification (700,000 units) there in May 2017.<ref name=\"auscert\" /> In New Zealand, ''25'' broke the record for highest first week sales, selling 18,766 copies. The previous record holder was [[Susan Boyle]] whose ''[[I Dreamed a Dream (album)|I Dreamed a Dream]]'' sold 17,435 copies in its first week.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Adele breaks NZ record with new album|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11552382|website=The New Zealand Herald|date=27 November 2015|accessdate=29 November 2015|issn=1170-0777 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719113551/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11552382 |archivedate=19 July 2018}}</ref> By the end of the year, ''25'' became the best-selling album of 2015 in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele's new album storms to top|url=http://m.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11564453|website=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=21 December 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116112645/https://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11564453 |archivedate=16 November 2018}}</ref> In South Africa, ''25'' achieved double platinum sales in five days through physical and digital vendors.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele on fast track with '25'|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/thetimes/2015/11/25/Adele-on-fast-track-with-25|website=Times LIVE|accessdate=29 November 2015 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125212202/http://www.timeslive.co.za/thetimes/2015/11/25/Adele-on-fast-track-with-25 |archivedate=25 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\nIn October 2015, numerous journalists speculated that other musicians had pushed back their albums in order to avoid chart competition with Adele; artists such as [[Justin Bieber]], [[Sam Smith (singer)|Sam Smith]] and [[One Direction]] all did this so that their sales would not be affected.<ref name=\"auto\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/34570462/adeles-new-track-other-artists-pushed-material-back-to-avoid-clash|title=Adele's new track: Other artists pushed material back to avoid clash \u2013 BBC Newsbeat|publisher=BBC|date=1 January 1970|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref> [[Columbia Records]] shipped 3.6 million physical copies of ''25'', across the United States, making it the most CDs shipped for a new release since the shipment of 2.4 million copies of NSYNC's ''No Strings Attached'' in 2000.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hughes|first=Deirdre|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/adele-s-new-album-may-break--impossible--sales-record-195030302.html|title=Adele's new album may break 'impossible' sales record|work=[[Yahoo!]] Finance|date=19 November 2015|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref> One million copies of ''25'' were shipped to UK retailers, including [[HMV]] and [[Tesco]]. Ian Topping, chief executive of HMV, stated that the company had a great start with the album and sales had exceeded their expectations, continuing to say it was their \"fastest selling album for many years.\"<ref name=\"independent1\">{{cite news|author=Adam Sherwin|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/adele-25-new-album-on-course-to-sell-a-million-copies-on-its-first-day-a6742416.html|title=Adele 25: New album on course to sell a million copies on its first day|work=[[The Independent]]|date=20 November 2015|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the album's release, journalists reported that ''25'' was able to encourage the public to return to buying physical copies, compared to streaming. Adam Shewin of ''[[The Independent]]'' stated that \"''25'' sent casual purchasers back to the remaining physical stores and may even have introduced a new generation to the delights of ownership.\"<ref name=\"independent1\" /> The album was described as saving the music industry, which was seeing dwindling profits with downloading and streaming as the popular methods of music consumption.<ref name=\"indereview\"/> The album was also noted for boosting sales of retailer [[Target Corporation|Target]], which sold the extra track edition of ''25'', during [[Thanksgiving]] and [[Black Friday (shopping)|Black Friday]]. Target Chief Executive Brian Cornell stated that ''25'' was \"the biggest release we've ever had \u2013 this is going to break all the records for us\" and that \"the combination of Adele dropping when it did, the weekend before Thanksgiving, really helped bring in people\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Adele Gives Target a Boost, CEO Says|url=http://fortune.com/2015/11/26/target-adele-black-friday/|website=Fortune|accessdate=27 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe album's first day sales in the US were 1.49 million, averaging at 62,000 copies per hour, and 1,000 copies per minute, while on iTunes, ''25'' sold 900,000 copies on its first day<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2015/12/03/5-statistics-that-highlight-how-amazing-adeles-25-really-is/|title=5 Statistics That Highlight How Amazing Adele's '25' Really Is|work=Forbes|accessdate=22 January 2016}}</ref> becoming the fastest-selling album in iTunes history, breaking the record previously held by [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s [[Beyonc\u00e9 (album)|self titled]] album.<ref>{{cite news|first=Clarisse|last=Loughrey|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/adeles-album-is-no1-in-almost-every-country-in-the-world-a6749626.html|title=Adele's new album 25 is No.1 on iTunes in almost every country in the world|date=26 November 2015|work=The Independent|accessdate=9 August 2016}}</ref> The album sold more copies in the US in its debut week than the previous number-one albums had sold in the previous 22 weeks combined. Additionally, it sold more copies in its first week than any album sold in an entire calendar year in three recent years (2008, 2009, and 2013).<ref name=\"yahoo.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/music/12-mind-boggling-facts-about-adeles-032640099.html|title=12 Mind-Boggling Facts About Adele's Record-Breaking Debut|date=28 November 2015}}</ref> ''25'' sold more copies in the US in its opening week than the next two best-selling albums of the year combined (Taylor Swift's ''1989'' and [[Drake (rapper)|Drake]]'s ''[[If You're Reading This It's Too Late]]'', which combined to sell 2.885 million copies in 2015).<ref name=\"yahoo.com\" /> ''25'' sold more copies in its first week than the next two fastest-selling albums by female artists combined\u2014[[Britney Spears]]'s ''[[Oops!... I Did It Again (album)|Oops!... I Did It Again]]'', which sold 1.319 million in its first week, and Swift's ''1989'', which sold 1.287 million in its first week.<ref name=\"yahoo.com\" />\n\nIt was stated by ''Billboard'' on 5 January 2016 that in 2015, overall [[album sales]] both digital and physical experienced a 6% decline compared to 2014. ''25'' is credited to having eased the decline of the continuing downfall of album sales. It was also noted that if it was not for the success of ''25'', the 6% decline would have been 9% as the album made up 3.1% of the entire album sales total of 2015.<ref name=\"caulfield1\" />\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Standard edition<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/25/id1051394208|title=iTunes (U.S.) \u2013 Music \u2013 Adele \u2013 25|accessdate=16 November 2015|date=20 November 2015|work=iTunes (U.S.)}}</ref>\n| all_writing = \n| collapsed = no\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| title1 = [[Hello (Adele song)|Hello]]\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Adele Adkins]]|[[Greg Kurstin]]}}\n| extra1 = Kurstin\n| length1 = 4:55\n| title2 = [[Send My Love (To Your New Lover)]]\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Adkins|[[Max Martin]]|[[Shellback (record producer)|Shellback]]}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|Martin|Shellback}}\n| length2 = 3:43\n| title3 = I Miss You\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Adkins|[[Paul Epworth]]}}\n| extra3 = Epworth\n| length3 = 5:48\n| title4 = [[When We Were Young (Adele song)|When We Were Young]]\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Adkins|[[Tobias Jesso Jr.]]}}\n| extra4 = [[Ariel Rechtshaid]]\n| length4 = 4:51\n| title5 = Remedy\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Adkins|[[Ryan Tedder]]}}\n| extra5 = Tedder\n| length5 = 4:05\n| title6 = [[Water Under the Bridge (song)|Water Under the Bridge]]\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Adkins|Kurstin}}\n| extra6 = Kurstin\n| length6 = 4:00\n| title7 = [[River Lea (song)|River Lea]]\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Adkins|[[Danger Mouse (musician)|Brian Burton]]}}\n| extra7 = [[Danger Mouse (musician)|Danger Mouse]]\n| length7 = 3:45\n| title8 = Love in the Dark\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Adkins|[[Samuel Dixon]]}}\n| extra8 = Dixon\n| length8 = 4:46\n| title9 = [[Million Years Ago (song)|Million Years Ago]]\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Adkins|Kurstin}}\n| extra9 = Kurstin\n| length9 = 3:47\n| title10 = [[All I Ask (Adele song)|All I Ask]]\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Adkins|[[Bruno Mars]]|[[Philip Lawrence (songwriter)|Philip Lawrence]]|Christopher Brody Brown}}\n| extra10 = [[The Smeezingtons]]\n| length10 = 4:32\n| title11 = Sweetest Devotion\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Adkins|Epworth}}\n| extra11 = Epworth\n| title12 = \n| length12 = \n| title13 = \n| length13 = \n| title14 = \n| length14 = \n| title15 = \n| length15 = \n| title16 = \n| length16 = \n| length11 = 4:12\n| title17 = \n| length17 = \n| title18 = \n| length18 = \n| title19 = \n| length19 = \n| title20 = \n| length20 = \n| total_length = {{Duration|m=48|s=25}}\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline  = [[Target Corporation|Target]] and Japanese bonus tracks<ref name=\"TargetUS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.target.com/p/adele-25-target-exclusive/-/A-50281802#prodSlot=medium_1_1&term=adele+25|title=Adele \u2013 25 \u2013 Target Exclusive : Target|accessdate=16 November 2015|date=20 November 2015|work=Target}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdjapan.co.jp/feature/adele_japanbonus_20151027|title=Adele New Album with 3 Japan Only Bonus Tracks|accessdate=27 October 2015|date=27 October 2015|work=cdjapan}}</ref>\n| collapsed  = yes\n| extra_column  = Producer(s)\n| title12  = Can't Let Go\n| writer12  = {{hlist|Adkins|[[Linda Perry]]}}\n| extra12  = Perry\n| length12  = 3:18\n| title13  = Lay Me Down\n| writer13  = {{hlist|Adkins|Jesso}}\n| extra13  = {{hlist|[[Mark Ronson]]|Lil Silva {{small|(additional)}}}}\n| length13  = 4:30\n| title14  = Why Do You Love Me\n| writer14  = {{hlist|Adkins|[[Rick Nowels]]}}\n| extra14  = Rechtshaid\n| length14  = 3:59\n| total_length  = {{Duration|m=60|s=12}}\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\nCredits adapted from [[AllMusic]] and album's [[liner notes]].<ref name=\"Target version booklet\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=25|others=[[Adele]]|year=2015|url=http://www.target.com/p/adele-25-target-exclusive/-/A-50281802|first=Adele|last=Adkins|pages=12\u201313|type=Booklet|publisher=[[XL Recordings]]|id=88875176782|location=London, England, U.K.}}</ref><ref name=\"Allmusic Credits\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/25-mw0002828987/credits|title=''25'' Credits|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=11 May 2016 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224062643/https://www.allmusic.com/album/25-mw0002828987/credits |archivedate=24 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Locations'''\n*Mixed at [[Electric Lady Studios]], New York; Capitol Studios, Los Angeles; MixStar Studios, [[Virginia Beach]]; Larrabee Studios, Los Angeles\n*Mastered at [[Sterling Sound]], New York\n\n'''Musicians'''\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Adele]] \u2013 [[vocals]] {{small|(all tracks)}}, [[drums]] {{small|(track 1)}}, [[guitar]] {{small|(track 2)}}, [[piano]] {{small|(track 11)}}\n*Leo Abrahams \u2013 guitar {{small|(track 13)}}\n*Victor Axelrod \u2013 piano {{small|(track 13)}}\n*Thomas Brenneck \u2013 guitar {{small|(track 13)}}\n*Christopher Brody Brown \u2013 piano {{small|(track 10)}}\n*Will Canzoneri \u2013 [[clavinet]], piano, and [[Rhodes piano|Rhodes]] {{small|(track 14)}}\n*[[Danger Mouse (musician)|Danger Mouse]] \u2013 piano, [[electric guitar]], [[organ (music)|organ]], and [[Programming (music)|programming]] {{small|(track 7)}}\n*[[Samuel Dixon]] \u2013 piano and [[synthesizer]] {{small|(track 8)}}\n*[[Paul Epworth]] \u2013 programming and [[Percussion instrument|percussion]] {{small|(tracks 3, 11)}}; drums, [[bass (sound)|bass]], piano, organ, and guitar {{small|(track 3)}}\n*FILMharmonic Orchestra \u2013 [[String instrument|strings]] {{small|(track 8)}}\n*Declan Gaffney \u2013 bass and percussion {{small|(track 7)}}\n*[[Este Haim]] \u2013 [[tambourine]] {{small|(track 13)}}\n*[[Emile Haynie]] \u2013 additional instrumentation {{small|(track 1)}}\n*Tom Herbert \u2013 bass {{small|(track 11)}}\n*[[Tobias Jesso Jr.]] 